<h2>Show notes</h2>
<ul>
 <li>Stevan Little on <a href="https://github.com/stevan">Github</a>. He works at <a href="http://www.iinteractive.com/">Infinity Interactive</a>.</li>
 <li>He is the author of <a href="http://moose.perl.org/">Moose</a>, the postmodern object system of Perl 5.</li>
 <li><a href="https://github.com/MoeOrganization/moe">Moe</a>, an -OFun prototype of an Ultra Modern Perl 5. (Written in Scala.) </li>
 <li>Moe contributor <a href="https://github.com/prakashk">Prakash Kailasa</a> known as "sahadev" on IRC was mentioned.
     He is using the <a href="http://aperiodic.net/phil/scala/s-99/">99 Scala Problems</a> for example driven development of Moe.</li>
 <li><a href="http://www.perl6.org/">Perl 6</a></li>
 <li><a href="https://metacpan.org/author/AUDREYT">Audrey Tang</a> and the mostly defunct <a href="http://www.pugscode.org/">Pugs project</a>.</li>
 <li><a href="https://metacpan.org/module/Class::MOP">Class::MOP</a> the Meta Object Protocol Moose sits on top of.</li>
 <li><a href="https://github.com/gaal">Gaal Yahas</a> and <a href="http://blog.woobling.org/">Yuval Kogman (nothingmuch)</a>, who came up with the name Moose.</li>
 <li><a href="http://blog.urth.org/">Dave Rolsky (autarch)</a> who rewrote the manual of Moose. (See the <a href="/dave-rolsky">interview with Dave Rolsky</a>)</li>
   Other names mentioned: <a href="http://www.trout.me.uk/">Matt Trout</a>,
   <a href="http://marcus.nordaaker.com/">Marcus Ramberg</a>,
   <a href="http://chris.prather.org/">Chris Prather (perigrin)</a>,
   <a href="http://tozt.net/">Jesse Luehrs (doy)</a>,
   <a href="https://metacpan.org/author/ETHER">Karen Etheridge (ether)</a></li>
</ul>

